        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-10-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-10-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="64"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <head>64. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="to">Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d64fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss>
                        Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–060, Senior Review Group Meetings,
                            <gloss target="#t_SRG1">SRG</gloss> Meeting Indian Ocean 10/6/71.
                        Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1971-10-28">October 28, 1971</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <head>MEMORANDUM FOR</head>
                    <item>The Under Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Deputy Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Director of Central Intelligence</item>
                    <item>The Deputy Director, <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss>
                    </item>
                    <item>The Chairman, Joint Chiefs of Staff</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Further Study of Indian Ocean Arms Control</item>
                </list>
                <p>As agreed at the Senior Review Group meeting of October 6,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d64fn2">See <ref target="#d61">Document 61</ref>.</note> the study
                    of Indian Ocean arms control should be further developed by the preparation of a
                    paper which specifically analyzes the issues raised in designing non-strategic
                    naval limitations in the Indian Ocean. Using as a point of departure Options II,
                    IV, and V of the arms control study prepared as a follow-on to <gloss
                        target="#t_NSSM1">NSSM</gloss> 110,<note n="3" xml:id="d64fn3">See <ref
                            target="#d57">Document 57</ref>.</note> the paper should concentrate on
                    such issues as: <pb facs="0242" n="209" xml:id="pg_209"/>
                    <list>
                        <item>—the comparative impact on the U.S. and <gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                                >USSR</gloss> of limitations on Indian Ocean bases and support
                            facilities;</item>
                        <item>—the question of distinguishing naval transits from exercises and
                            “show of force” maneuvers and of distinguishing all of these from a
                            permanent presence;</item>
                        <item>—the comparative impact on the U.S. and the <gloss target="#t_USSR1"
                                >USSR</gloss> (in terms of surge capability and reaction time) of
                            deployment limitations on non-strategic naval forces, both with and
                            without Indian Ocean bases and support facilities.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The issue of possible precedents which could be set by such Indian Ocean
                    limitations should be weighed in assessing the attractiveness of non-strategic
                    limitations as a means of dealing with the increased Soviet naval presence in
                    the area. Interagency differences should be clearly identified.</p>
                <p>The paper should be prepared by an Ad Hoc Group chaired by representatives of
                        <gloss target="#t_ACDA1">ACDA</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_DOD1"
                        >DOD</gloss> and comprising representatives of the addressees and the <gloss
                        target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Staff. It should be submitted to the Assistant
                    to the President for National Security Affairs no later than November 19.<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d64fn4">See <ref target="#d69">Document 69</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
